description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure. Fragmentary kalathos broken from figure of Hathor, together with parts of the wreaths that encircled her head. The kalathos has a scalloped edge. The kalathos is painted green with thin vertical lines in black paint; subsequent to this a white dressing was inexpertly applied to the wreaths, and presumably the whole figure, with a little inside the kalathos. Some pink paint on the lower part of the wreaths survives. Constructed in a hollow, from a two-piece mould. Red-brown Nile silt with a grey core, common mica and white inclusions.

Apparently solid, and probably from a two-piece mould, with all-over white dressing and face, ears and neck subsequently painted pink. Red-brown Nile silt fabric with grey core, fine gold mica, quartz and white (limestone, up to 4mm across) inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure, fragment of mans midrift. A fragment from a large-scale male figure, perhaps a deity, surviving from waist to knee. He is draped from the belly down in a himation, with a roll at the top edge held up at the left by his lost left hand. There is no back to the figure. Hand modelled; the drapery is indicated with deep incision. Skin of the belly has a dark pink slip. Orange clay with a reddish core, abundant fine mica and some white inclusions: possibly not of Egyptian origin.
